C ====================================================================
C DEADBAND FRAMEWORK — CELLULAR AUTOMATON IMPLEMENTATION
C ====================================================================
C
C Von Neumann invented BOTH the von Neumann architecture AND
C cellular automata. The irony: his non-von-Neumann invention
C (cellular automata) may be more fundamental than his von Neumann one.
C
C CELLULAR AUTOMATON FOR EISENSTEIN LATTICE:
C
C Grid: 2D hexagonal (each cell has 6 neighbors)
C Cell state: (lattice_point: bool, signal: float, snapped: bool)
C
C Rule 1 (SNAP): If signal exceeds threshold, snap to nearest lattice point
C   snapped = |signal - lattice_point| < deadband
C
C Rule 2 (PROPAGATE): Snapped cells propagate to neighbors
C   If neighbor is within deadband, it snaps too
C   This is WAVE PROPAGATION of the lattice snap
C
C Rule 3 (BMA): Linear cells store sequence bits
C   Each cell computes local discrepancy
C   Discrepancy propagates along the line
C   Convergence detected when discrepancy reaches zero for 2L cells
C
C ====================================================================
C THE HEXAGONAL CELLULAR AUTOMATON
C ====================================================================
C
C The Eisenstein lattice IS a hexagonal grid.
C A cellular automaton ON this grid is NATURAL:
C
C   Each cell = one Eisenstein lattice point
C   Cell state = (signal_value, snapped)
C   Update rule: if |signal - lattice_point| < deadband → snap
C   Propagation: snapped cells pull neighbors toward lattice
C
C THIS IS EXACTLY WHAT THE GPU SWARM DOES:
C   Each agent = one cell
C   Snap = lattice_point assignment
C   The "zero drift" result = the cellular automaton reaching equilibrium
C
C ====================================================================
C BMA AS 1D CELLULAR AUTOMATON
C ====================================================================
C
C Rule 110 (Wolfram) is Turing-complete.
C BMA is a specific 1D CA rule:
C
C   Cell state: (bit, connection_polynomial_bit, discrepancy)
C   Rule: compute discrepancy from neighbor bits
C   Update: if discrepancy ≠ 0, toggle connection polynomial
C   Detect: after 2L steps with zero discrepancy, pattern found
C
C The BMA algorithm IS a 1D cellular automaton rule.
C The 2L convergence IS the CA reaching a fixed point.
C
C ====================================================================
C /360 AS CYCLIC CELLULAR AUTOMATON
C ====================================================================
C
C A ring of 360 cells. Each cell has state 0 or 1.
C Adding two /360 values = shifting the 1-cells around the ring.
C Multiplication = repeated shifting.
C
C This is a CYCLIC TAG SYSTEM — another von Neumann-era concept.
C /360 arithmetic IS a tag system by another name.
C
C ====================================================================
C BACK-TRANSLATION INSIGHTS
C ====================================================================
C
C 1. THE GPU SWARM IS A CELLULAR AUTOMATON
C    We built a GPU swarm with 200K agents and zero drift.
C    This is a cellular automaton on the Eisenstein lattice.
C    The "zero drift" = the CA reached a fixed point.
C    The lattice IS the CA's equilibrium.
C
C 2. BMA IS A CA RULE, NOT AN ALGORITHM
C    Reframing BMA as a CA rule means:
C    - It can run on ANY CA hardware (including FPGAs, neural tissue)
C    - The 2L convergence = CA fixed point (topological guarantee)
C    - Parallel BMA = parallel CA update (trivially parallelizable)
C
C 3. /360 ARITHMETIC IS A TAG SYSTEM
C    The ring of 360 cells is a tag system.
C    Tag systems are Turing-complete.
C    Therefore /360 arithmetic can compute ANYTHING (slowly).
C    But for our purposes, it computes EXACT arithmetic (fast).
